benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: POST /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/block - Block a bundle

covered: Valid Payload: Successful block with required fields (TC01) and with all optional parameters (TC02).
Validation of inputs: Malformed payload (TC08) and invalid date format (TC11) and missing/invalid headers (TC09, TC18) coverage input validation and authorization.
Large Payloads: Stress test with large BlockingState payload (TC16).
Authorization scenarios: Missing/invalid authentication header or token (TC09, TC18).
Server Error Handling: Service unavailable (TC17) and dependent service error (TC28).
Security: Injection (TC19) and XSS payloads (TC20) are handled safely.
Regression: Special characters in BlockingState (TC23) and backward compatibility (TC24).
Performance: Response time tests under normal/peak load (TC25, TC26) and parallel blocking (TC27).
Integration: Data consistency across systems (TC29) and integration-related error handling (TC28).
gaps: Duplicate Submission: no tests for handling of duplicate POST submissions.
Rate Limiting: no tests for rate limiting/throttling.
Caching Behavior: no tests for caching headers (e.g., ETag, Cache-Control) on POST responses.
Expanded authorization edge cases: limited coverage beyond 401/400 (e.g., 403).
Additional failure modes: explicit 500 Internal Server Error scenarios? (beyond 503 in TC17/TC28).
Empty response handling and API behavior when no data is returned by the operation.
recommendations: Add a Duplicate Submission test to verify idempotency/deduplication behavior.
Introduce Rate Limiting/Throttling tests to ensure service resilience under bursty traffic.
Add tests for caching headers on POST responses where applicable, and clarify behavior for caching.
Enhance Authorization coverage with 403 Forbidden scenarios and permission-based access checks.
Add explicit 500 Internal Server Error tests (e.g., database failure) in addition to existing 503/502 scenarios.
Include an explicit test for empty or minimal responses where appropriate to confirm behavior.
